function twoSum(nums: number[], target: number): [number, number] {
  // for each number, check if (target - number) was already seen
  // use a Map<value, index> to look up complements in O(1)
}

solution:
function twoSum(nums: number[], target: number): [number, number] {
  const seen = new Map<number, number>();

  for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    const complement = target - nums[i];
    if (seen.has(complement)) {
      return [seen.get(complement)!, i];
    }
    seen.set(nums[i], i);
  }

  throw new Error("No two sum solution found");
}

description.en:
Implement `debounce`, a higher-order function that delays calling `func` until `delay` ms have passed since the *last* time the debounced function was invoked. Any call within the delay window resets the timer.

**Requirements:**
- Return a debounced wrapper around `func` with the same argument shape
- Each call within the delay window cancels the pending call and restarts the timer
- Only the arguments from the *last* call are passed to `func` when it finally runs
- Preserve `this` from the call site (so it works as an object method too)
- The returned function must have a `cancel()` method that clears any pending execution

**Function signature:**
```typescript
function debounce<T extends (...args: any[]) => any>(
  func: T,
  delay: number
): ((...args: Parameters<T>) => void) & { cancel: () => void }
```

**Example:**
```typescript
const search = debounce((query: string) => console.log('Searching:', query), 300);
search('a');
search('ab');
search('abc');
// only one call fires, 300ms after the last one: "Searching: abc"

const save = debounce(() => console.log('saved'), 500);
save();
save.cancel(); // 'saved' never logs
```

**Edge cases:**
- `cancel()` called with nothing pending is a no-op, not an error
- `this` must resolve correctly when the debounced function is used as `obj.method = debounce(fn, 100)`
- Rapid-fire calls (e.g. 100 calls in 10ms) must still only ever schedule a single pending timer

